In summary:
$$\begin{array}{ll}
5 \cdot 3=15 & -5(3)=-15 \\
5(-3)=-15 & (-5)(-3)=15
\end{array}$$

Notice that for multiplication of two signed numbers, when the
signs are the same, the product is positive.
signs are different, the product is negative.
What about division? Division is the inverse operation of multiplication. So, $15 \div 3=5$ because $5 \cdot 3=15$. In words, this expression says that 15 can be divided into 3 groups of 5 each because adding five three times gives 15 . If you look at some examples of multiplying integers, you might figure out the rules for dividing integers.
$$\begin{array}{lllll}
5 \cdot 3=15 & \text { so } 15 \div 3=5 & -5(3)=-15 & \text { so } & -15 \div 3=-5 \\
(-5)(-3)=15 & \text { so } & 15 \div(-3)=-5 & 5(-3)=-15 & \text { so } \\
& -15 \div(-3)=5
\end{array}$$

Division follows the same rules as multiplication with regard to signs.

\section*{Multiplication and Division of Signed Numbers}

For multiplication and division of two signed numbers:

\begin{tabular}{|c|c|}
\hline Same signs & Result \\
\hline - Two positives & Positive \\
\hline - Two negatives & Positive \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

If the signs are the same, the result is positive.

\begin{tabular}{|c|c|}
\hline Different signs & Result \\
\hline - Positive and negative & Negative \\
\hline - Negative and positive & Negative \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

If the signs are different, the result is negative.

