\section*{EXAMPLE 1.29}

Simplify: (a) $\frac{5 x}{6}-\frac{3}{10}$ (b) $\frac{5 x}{6} \cdot \frac{3}{10}$.

\section*{Solution}

First ask, "What is the operation?" Identifying the operation will determine whether or not we need a common denominator. Remember, we need a common denominator to add or subtract, but not to multiply or divide.
(a)

What is the operation? The operation is subtraction.

Do the fractions have a common denominator? No.
$$\frac{5 x}{6}-\frac{3}{10}$$

Find the LCD of 6 and 10 The LCD is 30.
$$\begin{aligned}
6 & =2 \cdot 3 \\
10 & =2 \cdot 5 \\
\hline \mathrm{LCD} & =2 \cdot 3 \cdot 5 \\
\mathrm{LCD} & =30
\end{aligned}$$

\begin{tabular}{|l|l|}
\hline Rewrite each fraction as an equivalent fraction with the LCD. & $\frac{5 x \cdot 5}{6 \cdot 5}-\frac{3 \cdot 3}{10 \cdot 3}$ \\
\hline & $\frac{25 x}{30}-\frac{9}{30}$ \\
\hline Subtract the numerators and place the difference over the common denominators. & $\frac{25 x-9}{30}$ \\
\hline Simplify, if possible. There are no common factors. The fraction is simplified. & \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

\begin{tabular}{|l|l|}
\hline What is the operation? Multiplication. & $\frac{5 x}{6} \cdot \frac{3}{10}$ \\
\hline To multiply fractions, multiply the numerators and multiply the denominators. & $\frac{5 x \cdot 3}{6 \cdot 10}$ \\
\hline Rewrite, showing common factors. Remove common factors. & $$\frac{\not p x \cdot \not p}{2 \cdot \not p \cdot 2 \cdot \not p}$$ \\
\hline Simplify. & $\frac{x}{4}$ \\
\hline Notice, we needed an LCD to add $\frac{5 x}{6}-\frac{3}{10}$, but not to multiply $\frac{5 x}{6} \cdot \frac{3}{10}$. & \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

