\section*{Multiply and Divide Decimals}

When we multiply signed decimals, first we determine the sign of the product and then multiply as if the numbers were both positive. We multiply the numbers temporarily ignoring the decimal point and then count the number of decimal points in the factors and that sum tells us the number of decimal places in the product. Finally, we write the product with the appropriate sign.

\section*{HOW TO}

Multiply decimals.
Step 1. Determine the sign of the product.
Step 2. Write in vertical format, lining up the numbers on the right. Multiply the numbers as if they were whole numbers, temporarily ignoring the decimal points.
Step 3. Place the decimal point. The number of decimal places in the product is the sum of the number of decimal places in the factors.
Step 4. Write the product with the appropriate sign.

