\section*{Convert Decimals, Fractions, and Percents}

In our work, it is often necessary to change the form of a number. We may have to change fractions to decimals or decimals to percent.

We convert decimals into fractions by identifying the place value of the last (farthest right) digit. In the decimal 0.03 . the 3 is in the hundredths place, so 100 is the denominator of the fraction equivalent to 0.03 .
$$0.03=\frac{3}{100}$$

The steps to take to convert a decimal to a fraction are summarized in the procedure box.

\section*{HOW TO}

Convert a decimal to a proper fraction and a fraction to a decimal.
Step 1. To convert a decimal to a proper fraction, determine the place value of the final digit.
Step 2. Write the fraction.
- numerator-the "numbers" to the right of the decimal point
- denominator-the place value corresponding to the final digit

Step 3. To convert a fraction to a decimal, divide the numerator of the fraction by the denominator of the fraction.

\section*{EXAMPLE 1.39}

Write: (a) 0.374 as a fraction (b) $-\frac{5}{8}$ as a decimal.
(J) Solution
(a)

\begin{tabular}{|l|l|l|}
\hline & \multicolumn{2}{|c|}{0.374} \\
\hline Determine the place value of the final digit. & 0.3 tenths & 7 hundredths \\
\hline Write the fraction for 0.374: The numerator is 374. The denominator is 1,000. & & $\frac{374}{1000}$ \\
\hline Simplify the fraction. & & \begin{tabular}{l}
$$2 \cdot 187$$ \\
$2 \cdot 500$
\end{tabular} \\
\hline Divide out the common factors. & & 187 500 \\
\hline & & so, $0.374=\frac{187}{500}$ \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
(b) Since a fraction bar means division, we begin by writing the fraction $\frac{5}{8}$ as $8 \longdiv { 5 }$. Now divide.

\begin{tabular}{l}
0.625 \\
\hline 8$) 5.000$ \\
$\frac{48}{20}$ \\
$\frac{16}{40}$ \\
$\underline{40}$
\end{tabular}
so, $-\frac{5}{8}=-0.625$

